Can the euro be fixed?
Paris—German Finance Minister Wolfgang Schäuble recently put the option of Greece exiting the euro on the table, hoping to send a signal that no member state can be exempt from the strict disciplines of the monetary union.
In fact, his proposal sparked a debate about the principles that underpin the euro, its governance model, and the rationale for its existence.
Two weeks before Schäuble's proposal, European leaders had already noticed the report about the future of the euro written by European Commission President Jean-Claude Juncker and his colleagues from other EU institutions. But the new debate about Greece has made many policymakers believe it necessary to return to the original starting point.
Meanwhile, citizens are questioning why they should share a single currency.
Does this make sense? Can consensus be reached about Greece's future?
Currencies are like nations, and establishing them requires mythology.
Tradition holds that the euro was Germany's political cost for reunification, paid to France.
Indeed, German reunification was merely the final step in a project that had taken shape in the 1980s to address a long-standing problem.
European governments were strongly against floating exchange rates, seeing them as incompatible with a single market; yet they also did not want to maintain a German central bank-led monetary regime in the long term.
True euro on German terms seems to be the best solution.
Now that we look back, German reunification was more of a curse than a blessing.
When the exchange rate was locked in 1999, Germany was overvalued and its economy was in difficulty; France was undervalued and its economy was booming.
In the following decade, imbalances grew between the re-emerging Germany, which suffered from low interest rates and credit booms, and other countries.
And as the global financial crisis hit in 2008, these conditions became the perfect storm.
No one knows what Europe would be like without the euro.
Would fixed exchange rates continue or collapse?
Would the deutsche mark overshoot again?
Would countries reintroduce trade barriers and end the single market?
Would a real estate bubble emerge in Spain?
Will there be more or less government reform?
It is impossible to establish a counterfactual baseline to assess the impact of the euro.
This is no reason for complacency.
Over the past 15 years, the eurozone economy has consistently underperformed, and its political institutions must take responsibility for this.
The real question is whether a common European currency remains important for the future.
This issue is often avoided because the costs of leaving the euro are unimaginably high (and could increase further if a eurozone breakup were to occur during a crisis and exacerbate mutual recriminations among participants).
Moreover, abolishing the euro might unleash dark forces of nationalism and protectionism.
But Kevin O’Rourke of Oxford University recently pointed out that this view is not sufficient.
Logically, this is equivalent to suggesting that a couple stay married because the divorce is too costly (and could worsen mutual recriminations if it were to occur during a crisis).
So, does the euro still matter?
Originally, people expected the euro to deliver three major economic benefits.
It was assumed that a monetary union would promote economic integration and secure Europe’s long-term growth.
Instead, eurozone intraregional trade and investment have grown tepidly, while growth potential has actually been diminished.
This is partly because governments have failed to go beyond monetary union and build the eurozone into an economic superpower, instead clinging to the power they retained.
This may make sense politically, but it makes no sense economically: the large internal market is one of Europe’s key assets, so opportunities to strengthen it must not be squandered.
Second, people hoped the euro would become one of the major international currencies (especially considering that few countries meet the necessary legal, market, and institutional requirements).
According to the latest data from the ECB, this hope has largely been realized.
The euro's international use is second only to the US dollar, an achievement that helps Europe continue to influence global economic order rather than becoming a minor player.
Third, people (not without naivety) believed that the institutions underpinning the euro could improve overall economic policy quality, as if the quality of European-wide policies inherently surpasses that of national policies.
After the 2008 global financial crisis, severe tests came: the eurozone overestimated the fiscal dimension of the crisis and underestimated its financial dimension, resulting in performance that was inferior to that of the US and the UK.
If the euro is to deliver prosperity, more policy reforms will need to be implemented.
But developing and implementing a schedule for these reforms requires broad agreement on the nature of the problems.
The ongoing debates over Greece illustrate how far Europe is from such a consensus: there are conflicting analyses of the roots of the debt crisis among participating countries, leading to contradictory prescriptions.
Richard Cooper of Harvard observed that early international public health cooperation was hampered by varying patterns of contagion: countries favored joint action, but struggled to agree on a coordinated plan because they disagreed on how diseases spread from one country to another.
Similarly, the eurozone countries favored joint action but struggled to agree on a coordinated plan because they disagreed on how diseases spread from one country to another.
This is the problem the eurozone faces today.
Luckily, this problem is not unsolvable. Major reforms such as establishing the European Stability Mechanism (ESM) and launching the banking union have shown this.
Inconsistencies have not prevented the ECB from taking decisive action, indicating that institutional governance is indeed important.
But reforms and actions only began recently, and under severe crisis pressure, this fact highlights the difficulties in reaching consensus.
Europe cannot delay and pretend any longer.
Eurozone members must establish a consistent agenda for governance and political reform to turn the monetary union into an engine of prosperity, or they will sink into a cycle of endless debate and crises until citizens lose patience or markets lose confidence.
Clarity is the prerequisite for serious discussions and grand reforms.
Today, all major parties involved have the duty to clarify what they see as indispensable, what they find unacceptable, and what they are prepared to trade for what they want.
